modules.description: This module implements polymorphic map structures with totally ordered keys, supporting operations like insertion, deletion, ordered traversal, and value transformations. It provides functions for merging, filtering, and comparing maps, along with converting between ordered bindings and sequences, handling key absence with optional return values. These capabilities are useful for applications requiring ordered key-value associations, such as priority queues or sorted data processing pipelines.

This module implements a balanced binary tree-based set structure for totally ordered elements, supporting efficient insertion, deletion, union, intersection, and difference operations alongside element queries. It provides transformations like mapping and filtering, ordered iteration, and conversions to and from sequences and lists, enabling use cases such as maintaining sorted collections, performing set algebra, or extracting ordered subsets for processing.

This module implements a balanced binary tree-based set structure for totally ordered elements, supporting efficient insertion, deletion, union, intersection, and difference operations. It provides functions for element membership checks, ordered iteration, and transformations like mapping and filtering. Concrete use cases include maintaining sorted collections of unique items, performing set algebra operations, and extracting ordered subsets for further processing.

This module implements polymorphic map structures with totally ordered keys, supporting insertion, deletion, ordered traversal, and value transformations. It provides functions for merging, filtering, and comparing maps, along with converting between ordered bindings and sequences, handling key absence with optional return values. Concrete use cases include priority queues and sorted data processing pipelines.

This module provides set and map implementations based on balanced binary trees. It supports operations like insertion, deletion, union, intersection, and ordered traversal, along with transformations and comparisons on sets and maps. Use cases include maintaining sorted unique collections, performing set algebra, implementing priority queues, and processing ordered data pipelines.
